    <stitle>DCM AND DDM DRUM TYPE PARKING BRAKE - ROCKWELL DUPLEX CAM MECHANICAL BRAKE - OPERATION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="operate" graphiccount="1">
        <title>OPERATION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0402102">Figure 2</hotlnk>for all Item numbers in parentheses.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0402102" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0402102" filename="../figg04/G0402102.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px"/>
            <caption>Figure 2. DCM Brake Operation</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. ACTUATOR LEVER</callout1>
                <callout1>2. CAM</callout1>
                <callout1>3. BRAKE SHOE</callout1>
                <callout1>4. ACTUATOR STRUT</callout1>
                <callout1>5. ANCHOR PIN</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>The brake is actuated by a lever, cam and actuator strut (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0402102">Figure 2</hotlnk>). Applying force to the lever (Item 1) rotates the cam (Item 2).
            This action applies an outward force to the brake shoe in contact with the cam (Item 2). The actuator strut
            (Item 4), which is also in contact with the cam transmits an equal force to the opposite shoe (Item 3). When
            the linings contact the surface of the drum, friction forces counteract the rotation of the brake drum.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
